\noindent\textbf{Zero-shot (ZS).} The model receives a prompt instructing it to generate a structured English clinical summary covering chief complaint, symptoms, investigations, treatment, and follow-up, without introducing unsupported medical claims.

\noindent\textbf{Few-Shot (FS).} This augments the ZS prompt with $k{=}1$ demonstration examples (dialogue paired with gold summary) from the training set to condition the model on the desired structure.

\noindent\textbf{Translation (Trans).} Source dialogues are translated to English using IndicTrans2~\citep{gala2023indictrans2}, then summarized under the ZS English prompt. We hypothesize this routes processing through the LLMs' strongest generation language.

\noindent\textbf{Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT).} Models are fine-tuned via LoRA on the multilingual training set (rank $r{=}8$, $\alpha{=}32$, dropout $0.05$). Training runs for 3 epochs (AdamW, LR $2 \times 10^{-5}$, effective batch size 8) using 4-bit NF4 quantization and gradient checkpointing. 

\subsection{Evaluation Framework}
We employ a three-tier framework. \textbf{(1) Lexical Similarity:} ROUGE-L~\citep{lin2004rouge} and BERTScore~\citep{zhang2019bertscore} evaluate surface overlap, included primarily for comparability with prior work. \textbf{(2) LLM-as-judge:} GPT-4.1 scores summaries (1--5 Likert) on \textit{Truthfulness} (grounding), \textit{Safety} (absence of harmful omissions/fabrications), and \textit{Explainability} (clarity and correct attribution). \textbf{(3) Clinical entity analysis:} GPT-4.1 extracts Symptoms, Diagnoses, Substances/Habits, Procedures/Tests, and Treatments from both source and generation to calculate True Positives, False Positives (Hallucinations), and False Negatives (Omissions).

