\subsection{Few-Shot Degradation}
\label{sec:fewshot}
Adding same-language demonstrations makes things worse across most conditions. Macro-average entity F1 falls from 0.518 to 0.499 (Qwen) and 0.432 to 0.385 (Mistral), while hallucination rates rise. We identify three mechanisms: \textit{Template lock} (adhering strictly to the demo structure, causing omissions), \textit{Entity bleed} (demonstration entities migrating into the test patient's summary), and \textit{Calibration disruption} (interfering with a model's already-calibrated prior, notably causing Mistral-English F1 to drop from 0.652 to 0.558). The only exceptions (Qwen-Gujarati and Mistral-Telugu) occurred where zero-shot hallucination was pathologically high ($>69\%$), indicating FS helps only when zero-shot is severely miscalibrated. Furthermore, ROUGE/BERTScore are nearly insensitive to these critical clinical changes, confirming surface metrics are insufficient for medical safety.

\subsection{The Translation Typological Split}
Translation results reveal a clean typological split (Table~\ref{tab:translation_vs_zs}). For Indo-Aryan languages with Devanagari-related scripts, IndicTrans2 improves F1 (Mistral-Marathi gains +0.150). However, for Dravidian languages, F1 plummets (Qwen-Telugu drops 0.209, Kannada and Tamil degrade similarly). Complex verb forms and conditional structures are mistranslated, causing a \textit{mistranslation cascade} where the summarizer operates on degraded input. Assamese and Bengali also degrade, showing script family alone does not guarantee translation quality. Across all conditions, translation produces the lowest safety scores; direct zero-shot inference is safer than translation for Dravidian and low-resource languages.

